<subSubSection id="D7CE302C9FF0168994E7D7162C51EA67" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="7776E18183EA01CE1D1216C5E5370285" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8A32A5F79D45C0F5007F251147795C99" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Body length: male 10-12 mm. Males are entirely black without pale wing markings, the face is black medially, and there is no fascia of golden pile along the mesonotal transverse suture. Males are clearly more slender than 
<taxonomicName id="E8B76386604CD8DD1C3C29EBF9D84157" genus="P." lsidName="P. satyricus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="satyricus">
<emphasis id="2B19698CD6747DFC7C514B80E3EFFA7D" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. satyricus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which has a produced vertex.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6EB71FD1E2DC8DC5B4ECC95032A7BB49" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The female is not known with certainty, but one specimen from Peru possibly belongs to this species. In contrast with the male, the female has large yellowish white subapical wing patches (
<figureCitation id="2841FB783EC77CD833308C75AC2B6D64" captionStart="Figures 240–245" captionStartId="F41" captionText="Figures 240 - 245. 240 - 242 Peradon satyricus male, holotype: 240 habitus lateral 241 head frontal 242 scutellum dorsal 243 Peradon sciarus male holotype: habitus lateral 244, 245 Peradon cf. sciarus female: 244 habitus lateral 245 habitus dorsal." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.896.36493.figures240-245" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/362311" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.896.36493.figures240-245">Figs 244</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="7FA08D040563CAA34B60F60F2C3456EF" captionStart="Figures 240–245" captionStartId="F41" captionText="Figures 240 - 245. 240 - 242 Peradon satyricus male, holotype: 240 habitus lateral 241 head frontal 242 scutellum dorsal 243 Peradon sciarus male holotype: habitus lateral 244, 245 Peradon cf. sciarus female: 244 habitus lateral 245 habitus dorsal." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.896.36493.figures240-245" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/362311" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.896.36493.figures240-245">245</figureCitation>
), which make it look like 
<taxonomicName id="57B42090A8BE630AB2C91C86564A009A" genus="P." lsidName="P. niger" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="niger">
<emphasis id="A1ED674FE4DFA50473D98AD0DCD81ACB" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. niger</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="87ACEBBFEF94F17A3E77DE03FBFABEE5" genus="P." lsidName="P. normalis" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="normalis">
<emphasis id="11E2EE5B535E85B758BCFC86C2F724F9" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. normalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="0480DF89D9C2D07222D41E485A0FDFD8" genus="P." lsidName="P. pompiloides" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="pompiloides">
<emphasis id="AB57085ECC1DB3EC4D40DA76509E3CE8" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. pompiloides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. From 
<taxonomicName id="13D3473BADA3D0410627318D3FC0A9BB" genus="P." lsidName="P. niger" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="niger">
<emphasis id="2C12BC577F598FEAE9C1D14A94B10D5A" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. niger</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
it differs by the partly bare alula. From 
<taxonomicName id="5B80CB3BEB925868D83BECD341D47FD5" genus="P." lsidName="P. normalis" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="normalis">
<emphasis id="48804249A7972FC0339F859A02BC9EA1" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. normalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
it differs by the absence of a fascia of golden pile along the mesonotal transverse suture, the presence of a large basomedian patch of greyish pruinescence on tergite 4, and the absence of such pruinescence on the basal 1/3 of tergite 3. From 
<taxonomicName id="C715C1F930F30EDE5575D3F284427BCB" genus="P." lsidName="P. pompiloides" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="pompiloides">
<emphasis id="83EA2FEE7D69A84D7F1A99B8995BEDB9" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. pompiloides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
it differs by the partly bare wing cell br.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="ADAFE663D83DFF3A462A048685AABC72" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph id="B251E1DE684048501EF4B8AFA0E46004" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="562B55DDF7B1D33176EDA9E8407DB670" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">The male specimens from Colombia and Peru are 1-2 mm larger than the male type specimens from Surinam and French Guiana, and their wings are a little darker.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4CB9CABCE4B93A2BB98C73F74636B1A8" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The genitalia figured in 
<figureCitation id="A54CF4FFB823F14AB9126CED212A0A66" captionStart="Figures 262–267" captionStartId="F45" captionText="Figures 262 - 267. Male genitalia of Peradon species 262 P. hermetoides holotype 263 P. elongatus holotype 264 P. oligonax Colombia NHMUK 265 P. satyricus holotype 266 P. sciarus paratype 267 P. bidens Suriname RMNH." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.896.36493.figures262-267" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/362315" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.896.36493.figures262-267">Fig. 266</figureCitation>
are those of the holotype. 
<bibRefCitation id="D897D444C60FC163E7A84ACB2B1B6308" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1163/22119434-00002035" author="Reemer, M" journalOrPublisher="Tijdschrift voor Entomologie" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="27 - 57" refId="B24" refString="Reemer, M, 2014. A review of Microdontinae (Diptera: Syrphidae) of Surinam, with a key to the Neotropical genera. Tijdschrift voor Entomologie 157: 27 - 57" title="A review of Microdontinae (Diptera: Syrphidae) of Surinam, with a key to the Neotropical genera." url="https://doi.org/10.1163/22119434-00002035" volume="157" year="2014">Reemer (2014)</bibRefCitation>
figures the genitalia of the paratype, but in less detail and also from a slightly oblique angle, instead from a proper lateral view. The figure in the present paper should be considered more accurate.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A377BADFDF51E7830D66FCECC3FF6668" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The female from Peru here identified as 
<taxonomicName id="BE06323AE4AFAACAA5658EA0B37B5AB5" genus="P." lsidName="P. sciarus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="sciarus">P. cf. sciarus</taxonomicName>
is assigned to this species based on the COI barcode, which is almost identical to that of a Peruvian male of 
<taxonomicName id="A208907EDC51E53BE63AE17DDCC78F7B" genus="P." lsidName="P. sciarus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="sciarus">
<emphasis id="5FF9715EFF841E5DE519B544122B278B" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. sciarus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, from which it differs in one single nucleotide (
<figureCitation id="75B90AA99A33941F5E7CA995DA92B503" captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 8. Maximum Likelihood tree of COI barcodes of Peradon species. The scale at the bottom is a distance scale for the number of substitutions per site. Information on the barcoded specimens can be found in Table 1." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.896.36493.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/362273" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.896.36493.figure8">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
). The most striking difference of this female with the males is the presence of a large yellowish white subapical wing patch (
<figureCitation id="DFD07901962647BFCB286E7F25996641" captionStart="Figures 240–245" captionStartId="F41" captionText="Figures 240 - 245. 240 - 242 Peradon satyricus male, holotype: 240 habitus lateral 241 head frontal 242 scutellum dorsal 243 Peradon sciarus male holotype: habitus lateral 244, 245 Peradon cf. sciarus female: 244 habitus lateral 245 habitus dorsal." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.896.36493.figures240-245" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/362311" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.896.36493.figures240-245">Figs 244</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="CB761D9E59FC4EE344B81E49B5107F58" captionStart="Figures 240–245" captionStartId="F41" captionText="Figures 240 - 245. 240 - 242 Peradon satyricus male, holotype: 240 habitus lateral 241 head frontal 242 scutellum dorsal 243 Peradon sciarus male holotype: habitus lateral 244, 245 Peradon cf. sciarus female: 244 habitus lateral 245 habitus dorsal." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.896.36493.figures240-245" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/362311" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.896.36493.figures240-245">245</figureCitation>
). Similar cases of sexual dimorphism in wing colouration occur in other 
<taxonomicName id="1B3B9C27F0E3CA34A3884506F8CCA464" authority="Reemer, 2013" authorityName="Reemer" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Peradon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Peradon" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="682F98F36044FAF0943993819EC87534" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Peradon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species (e.g., 
<taxonomicName id="C9DAB2403425B9EEC288F33C35123B82" genus="P." lsidName="P. chrysopygus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="chrysopygus">
<emphasis id="7EA4410E9A6990722E7905BE8E657812" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. chrysopygus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), so this does not contradict the hypothesis that this female belongs to 
<taxonomicName id="A45D206B3F4B38EE2A17B0EFFD91B792" genus="P." lsidName="P. sciarus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="sciarus">
<emphasis id="4C595EB00669227D89E9A3AF438192BD" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. sciarus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. This female is also similar to the males in other characters, such as the absence of a fascia of golden pile along the mesonotal transverse suture, the partially bare wing cell br and the partly bare alula.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="EAEB174629175BE8C000654765EEE5BF" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="4712168FC2D8BB16F8DC10021B0A8DFB" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="45D6C6DFD3FDEA3F30F2553B78D7CFD8" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Known from Colombia, French Guiana, Peru, and Suriname.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
